    "## 8. Executive Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "**Problem.** Detect fraudulent credit-card transactions from 284,807 European card transactions (Sept. 2013),\n",
    "of which only 492 (0.17%) are fraud. Features are 28 anonymised PCA components plus `Time` and `Amount`.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Source evaluated.** `shakiliitju/Credit-Card-Fraud-Detection-Using-Machine-Learning`, which trains KNN and\n",
    "Decision-Tree models and reports **~100% accuracy** as evidence of success.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What we did.** Reproduced the source on the real data, then stress-tested its claim with a proper metric suite\n",
    "(precision, recall, F1, F2, MCC, ROC-AUC, PR-AUC) and three experiments: the accuracy illusion, data\n",
    "leakage / duplicate contamination, and the k=1 / imbalance-handling choices. We also trained honest baselines\n",
    "(class-weighted logistic regression and random forest, and an imbalance-aware XGBoost).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Key findings.** (1) Accuracy is meaningless here - a do-nothing model already scores 99.83%, and the source's\n",
    "own KNN is the **weakest** model by PR-AUC (0.71). (2) The source's leakage is real but, on this large dataset,\n",
    "numerically negligible; duplicate contamination is also minor (PR-AUC 0.872 -> 0.830 after dedup). (3) The k=1\n",
    "choice is poor: k=5 already lifts PR-AUC to 0.84, and an imbalance-aware XGBoost reaches **0.87** with a tunable\n",
    "precision/recall trade-off.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Bottom line.** The author's headline is an artefact of the wrong metric on an imbalanced problem, not a strong\n",
    "detector. The genuine, defensible performance is PR-AUC ~0.87 - good, but a different and more honest claim."
