    "## 9. Summing It Up\n",
    "\n",
    "**Were the author's claims supported?** No. The ~100% accuracy is technically reproducible but does not mean the\n",
    "model detects fraud; on a 0.17%-positive problem, accuracy is dominated by the legitimate class and a trivial\n",
    "baseline matches it. Judged by metrics appropriate to fraud (recall, precision, PR-AUC), the source's KNN is the\n",
    "weakest of the models we tried.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Most important insights.** (1) Pick the metric for the problem: under extreme imbalance, accuracy and even\n",
    "ROC-AUC can mislead, while PR-AUC and the precision/recall trade-off tell the real story. (2) Rigour means\n",
    "*measuring* the impact of a suspected flaw, not assuming it - here the leakage was real but harmless, which is a\n",
    "finding in itself. (3) Simple modelling choices (k, class weights, threshold) matter more than the headline\n",
    "number suggests.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Do we recommend this source as a template for similar problems?** Not as published - its evaluation would give\n",
    "a false sense of security on any imbalanced security task. With the corrections here (proper metrics, imbalance\n",
    "handling, threshold control) the underlying dataset and approach are a reasonable starting point.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Final conclusion.** The fraud-detection task is genuinely learnable (PR-AUC ~0.87), but the source's claim of\n",
    "success rests on the wrong yardstick. The lasting lesson is methodological: in cybersecurity ML, where the events\n",
    "that matter are rare, the choice of evaluation metric *is* the result."
